07661nam a22010095i 9780231512091DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20072007nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2007010371  a(OCoLC)1002232687  a(OCoLC)1004867982  a(OCoLC)1011439356  a(OCoLC)979909875  a(OCoLC)987921681  a(OCoLC)992525102  a(OCoLC)999359472  a97802315120917 a10.7312/calo141922doi  a(DE-B1597)458711  a(OCoLC)427864324  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHG187.C6bC438 2007 7aBUS0350002bisacsh04a330.95100aChina's Financial Transition at a Crossroads /ced. by Charles Calomiris. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (432 p.) :b47 figures and 44 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Acronyms -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. China’s Financial Markets: An Overview -- t2. China’s Banking Sector and Economic Growth -- t3. Understanding the Structure of Cross- Border Capital Flows: The Case of China -- t4. Financial Openness and the Chinese Growth Experience -- t5. The Effects of Stock Market Listing on the Financial Per for mance of Chinese Firms -- t6. China’s Exchange Rate Regime: The Long and Short of It -- t7. China’s Foreign Exchange Policy: What Will China Do? What Should China Do? -- tAppendix 1 Regional Estimates of New Deposit and Loan Shares, and Nonperforming Loans -- tAppendix 2. Evolution of Capital Controls in China -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aChina's increasing role in global economic affairs has placed the country at a crossroads: how many and what types of international capital-market transactions will China permit? How will China's financial system change internally? What kind of relationships will the Chinese government develop with foreign financial institutions, especially with those based in the United States? Can China broker a sustainable partnership with America that will avoid sending economic shock waves throughout the world?Drawing on the contemporary research of prominent international scholars, the experts in this volume outline the trajectory of China's financial markets since the advent of reform and anticipate their uncertain future. Chapter authors and commentators include Geert Bekaert, Loren Brandt, Lee Branstetter, Mary Wadsworth Darby, Michael DeStefano, Barry Eichengreen, Campbell Harvey, Fred Hu, Xiaobo Lu, Christian Lundblad, Ailsa Roell, Daniel Rosen, Shang-Jin Wei, Jialin Yu, and Xiaodong Zhu. The book begins with an overview of the history of financial-sector development, regulation, and performance and then focuses on the banking sector, discussing the progress, challenges, and prospects of current sector reform. Subsequent chapters describe the role of foreign capital in China's development and analyze the changes in capital flows and controls over time; explore various explanations for China's composition of foreign-capital and foreign-exchange policies, particularly the factors shaping China's reliance on foreign direct investment; and provide an international, comparative perspective on the remarkable growth experience of China and the contribution of its institutional environment to that experience. Contributors dispute the belief that stock market listing has done little to reform state-owned enterprises and take a hard look at the exchange rate regime choice for China, considering the potential long-run desirability of flexibility and the appropriate sequencing of reforms in foreign-exchange policy, domestic banking reform, and capital-market openness. The book concludes with a roundtable discussion in which prominent economists, including Peter Garber, Robert Hodrick, John Makin, David Malpass, Frederic Mishkin, and Eswar Prasad, debate the pace of the appreciation of China's currency and the likely consequences of that policy within and outside of China.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aFinancezChinavCongresses. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / International / General.2bisacsh1 aBekaert, Geert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandt, Loren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBranstetter, Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalomiris, Charles W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalomiris, Charles, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEichengreen, Barry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarber, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvey, Campbell R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHodrick, Robert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHu, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLundblad, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMakin, John H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalpass, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMishkin, Frederic S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrasad, Eswar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWei, Shang-Jin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZhu, Xiaodong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Packa